 plain Chinese was situated at the nexus between, on the one hand, the traditional standard of biliteracy characteristic of literary practices in the Sinographic sphere, and on the other, practices of translational multilingualism (competence in multiple spoken languages to produce a fully localized target text). Translations from plain Chinese are shown to carve out new ecologies of translations that not only enrich our understanding of early modern translation practices across the Sinographic sphere, but also demonstrate that the transregional uses of a non-alphabetic graphic technology call for different models of translation theory.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jul 2022) 0aTranslating and interpretingzEast Asia. 0aTranslating and interpretingzSoutheast Asia. 4aAsia. 4aAsian Studies. 4aEast Asia and North East Asia. 4aHistory. 4aLanguage Studies. 4aLinguistics. 4aTranslation and interpretation. 7aHISTORY / Asia / China.2bisacsh  aTranslation, language ecologies, sinographic sphere.1 aFraleigh, Matthew, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuo, Li, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuo, Li, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHedberg, William C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKing, Ross, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKornicki, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKornicki, Peter, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKyun Oh, Young, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLing, Xiaoqiao, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMa, Xiaolu, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPark, Si Nae, ec